        reading: { title: "What Would Happen If Pollinators Disappeared?", genre: "Science and environment explainer", paragraphs: ["If bees and other pollinators disappeared, humans would not immediately lose every type of food. Crops such as wheat, rice and potatoes do not depend completely on animal pollination. However, our diets would become much less varied because many fruits, nuts, seeds and vegetables rely on pollinators at least partly.", "The Food and Agriculture Organization reports that animal pollination affects about thirty-five percent of global crop production by volume. If pollinator numbers fell further, some foods could become harder and more expensive to produce. Farmers who grow coffee, cocoa or fruit might also lose an important part of their income.", "The effect would reach beyond farms. Many wild plants need insects or other animals to produce seeds. If those plants declined, birds and other species would have fewer sources of food and shelter.", "Scientists wish the causes were simple, but pollinators face several pressures, including habitat loss, pesticides and climate change. If farms and cities provided more native flowers and safer habitats, they could support a wider range of pollinating species."], vocabulary: [["pollinator", "polinizador"], ["rely on", "depender de"], ["crop", "cultivo agrícola"], ["habitat loss", "perda de habitat"]], questions: [rq("Which three foods would not disappear immediately without animal pollination?", "Wheat, rice and potatoes."), rq("What percentage of global crop production is affected by animal pollination?", "About thirty-five percent."), rq("How could fewer pollinators affect farmers financially?", "Some crops could become harder to produce, reducing farmers' income."), rq("Which local action could support more pollinating species?", "Providing native flowers and safer habitats.")] },
