        reading: { title: "The Argument That Helped Save the Eiffel Tower", genre: "History of a persuasive idea", paragraphs: ["The Eiffel Tower was built for the 1889 Universal Exhibition in Paris. It attracted enormous attention, but its future was not guaranteed. Gustave Eiffel had received permission to use the site for only twenty years, so the structure could have been dismantled around 1910.", "Eiffel understood that beauty and popularity might not be enough to protect it. He emphasized a more practical argument: the tower could serve science and communication. Experiments in weather, aerodynamics and wireless telegraphy were carried out from the structure.", "Its height made it particularly valuable for sending radio signals. A successful wireless link was created between the tower and the Panthéon in 1898, and it was later used for military radio. These results gave decision-makers a concrete reason to preserve the building.", "To sum up, the tower survived because Eiffel connected a famous monument with a useful public function. His case was persuasive because it answered the strongest objection: if the structure took up permanent space, it needed to provide lasting value. Radio helped demonstrate that value."], vocabulary: [["dismantle", "desmontar"], ["emphasize", "enfatizar"], ["wireless telegraphy", "telegrafia sem fio"], ["preserve", "preservar"]], questions: [rq("Why could the tower have been dismantled around 1910?", "Eiffel had permission to use the site for only twenty years."), rq("Which practical use did Eiffel emphasize?", "The tower could support science and communication."), rq("What did the tower's height make especially effective?", "Sending radio signals."), rq("Why was Eiffel's argument persuasive?", "He showed that the tower could provide lasting public value, not only visual interest.")] },
